message: To get a good score, first use 'water' on a raw ingredient, then use the 'stove' on the 'soaked' ingredient to make it 'cooked'. Combining a 'cooked vegetable' with a 'grain' will give you 20 points. Adding a 'cooked protein' to this combination will increase the value to 40. message: Focus on cooking ingredients first: use 'water' then 'stove' for vegetables and some grains (like wheat); use 'stove' directly for proteins and some grains (like tortillas). Raw eggs combine well with cooked vegetables to make a 20-value item, but are consumed. The most reliable path to high scores (40-60) is combining a 'cooked protein' with a 'cooked grain', or a 'cooked protein' with a 'cooked vegetable'. Avoid combining more than two already combined or complex items, as this often leads to 'overcomplicated' items with negative values. Submit when you have a valuable item and no simple, clear next step to increase value.

message: Always cook raw protein (egg, beans, beef) first, it immediately gives 20 value. Vegetables (e.g., beet, mushroom, tomato, broccoli) need to be soaked with water, then cooked with the stove. Combine cooked protein with one cooked vegetable for 40 value. Some grains (like rice or wheat) also need soaking then cooking, and can add 20 value by themselves, then increase the dish to 80 value when combined with a protein-vegetable dish. Be careful: adding too many ingredients, especially a zero-value cooked grain like corn or bread, will 'overcomplicate' the dish and give negative value. Aim for a cooked protein, one cooked vegetable, and one cooked (valuable) grain for 80 points, then submit.
